\begin_layout Section
Fluid Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fluids are a class of materials which are usefull for transferring heat
 energy in a heat pump.
 In principle there is nothing special about fluids, as nearly all materials
 will turn into a solid if it is cold enough, and melt to a liquid, and
 then vapourize to a gas if heated enough.
 However we usually want to utillize a heat pump within a narrow range of
 temperatures, which are within a few hundred degrees of waters freezing
 point.
 We also want a very safe system, so we do not want extreme pressures in
 our machines.
 A small set of materials allows us to use them for the heat moving material
 as we need the material to be a gas when we compress it, and a liquid when
 heat transfer has been done on the hot side of the process.
 We call materials that fall in this catergory of usefullness for fluids.
 Some are pure, and naturally occuring fluids like Ammonia or Propane, and
 others are mixtures, where the mixture is made to achieve a specific set
 of properties.
\end_layout

